!!Deities of Forsooth
!!!Armok, Overdeity
''God of Blood''<br>
''Alignment'': Unknown<br>
Armok is known as the "God of Blood", but not in a malicious sense. Armok does not promote death or slaughter. Nor does he promote health and wellness. Armok's purview is focused on the cycle of life. Blood is liquid, fluid, and flows from one place to another, be if from one organ to another or from a wound into the soil. Life is fluid, with beings moving about, interacting, living, and dying. Life force is recycled from once being to another, and Armok's grand metaphor for life is blood. Armok also has purview over the golden ichor flowing through the veins of the gods, and so all other deities have been granted godhood by Armok himself. As an overdeity, Armok has very little, if any, divine presence in mortal affairs. He does not grant spells, and he does not answer prayers, but it certainly doesn't stop mortal culture from saying a little prayer to him every now and then.<br>
Armok is the most well-known of all the gods, and "Blood of Armok" is a common swear uttered by mortals (roughly equivalent to "Jesus Christ" or "for God's sake"). Prayers to Armok are commonly made before battles, and rites are made to Armok at funerals.

!!!Standard-Tier Deities
Most other D&D 3.5 deities are well known and worshiped, however, some of the lore is a bit different. Zaurus was not a god in the past, as humans have only come into existence recently. Pelor is the god of time and the sun. Many humans give Pelor praise, but some revere other deities that may or may not actually exist. Kurtalmak is dead, and the kobolds worship actual dragons or sometimes even Ioun.
Ioun is the goddess of the dragons, replacing Bahamut and Tiamat, and is Neutral.

